ol.li:
for each { x } \xrightarrow {{ f }}{ y } and { y } \xrightarrow {{ g }}{ z } in B and objects \bar {x} \in  E _{ x } ,  \bar {y} \in  E _{ y } ,  \bar {z} \in  E _{ z }, a function

  \mathbf {hom} _{ E _{ f } } { \mathopen {} \left ( \bar {x} , \bar {y} \right ) \mathclose {}}   \times   \mathbf {hom} _{ E _{ g } } { \mathopen {} \left ( \bar {y} , \bar {z} \right ) \mathclose {}}   \to   \mathbf {hom} _{ E _{ f;g } } { \mathopen {} \left ( \bar {x} , \bar {z} \right ) \mathclose {}}      

that we will denote like ordinary (diagrammatic) function composition,

such that the following equations hold:

               1 _{ \bar {x} } ; \bar {h} =  \bar {h} \qquad       \bar {h}; 1 _{ \bar {y} }  =  \bar {h} \qquad       \bar {f};( \bar {g}; \bar {h}) = ( \bar {f}; \bar {g}); \bar {h}     


    Note that these are well-defined because of the corresponding laws for the base category B.

